Step 1 – Create DynamoDB Table

Open AWS Console.
Go to Amazon DynamoDB.
Click Create Table.

Use the following configuration:

Table Name
contact-form-data

Partition Key
id (String)

Click Create Table.

Step 2 – Create Lambda Function

Open AWS Lambda.
Click Create Function.
Choose Author from Scratch.

Use the following configuration:

Function Name
contactFormFunction

Runtime
Python 3.x

Click Create Function.

Step 3 – Lambda Function Code

Replace the default Lambda code with the following Python code.

import json
import boto3
import uuid

dynamodb = boto3.resource('dynamodb')
table = dynamodb.Table('contact-form-data')

def lambda_handler(event, context):

body = json.loads(event['body'])

name = body['name']
email = body['email']
message = body['message']

item = {
    'id': str(uuid.uuid4()),
    'name': name,
    'email': email,
    'message': message
}

table.put_item(Item=item)

return {
    'statusCode': 200,
    'headers': {
        'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': '*'
    },
    'body': json.dumps('Message stored successfully')
}

After adding the code, click Deploy.

Step 4 – Add DynamoDB Permission to Lambda

Go to the Lambda function Configuration tab.
Click Permissions.
Open the Execution Role.

Click Add Permissions and attach the following policy:

AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess

This allows the Lambda function to write data to DynamoDB.

Step 5 – Create API Gateway

Open Amazon API Gateway.
Click Create API.
Select HTTP API.

Add an integration with the Lambda function:

Lambda → contactFormFunction

Create the following route:

POST /contact

Deploy the API and copy the Invoke URL.

Example:

https://xxxxx.execute-api.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/prod/contact

Step 6 – Create Contact Form (Frontend)

Create a file called contact.html and add the following code.

<!DOCTYPE html> <html> <head> <title>Contact Form</title> </head> <body> <h2>Contact Us</h2> <form id="contactForm">

Name
<input type="text" id="name" required>

Email
<input type="email" id="email" required>

Message

<textarea id="message" required></textarea>

<button type="submit">Send</button>

</form> <script> document.getElementById("contactForm").addEventListener("submit", async function(e){ e.preventDefault(); const data = { name: document.getElementById("name").value, email: document.getElementById("email").value, message: document.getElementById("message").value }; await fetch("YOUR_API_ENDPOINT", { method: "POST", headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" }, body: JSON.stringify(data) }); alert("Message Sent Successfully"); }); </script> </body> </html>

Replace YOUR_API_ENDPOINT with your API Gateway URL.

Step 7 – Run the Contact Form Locally

Start a simple Python server by running the following command:

python -m http.server

Open the form in your browser using:

http://localhost:8000/contact.html

Submit the form.

Step 8 – Verify Data in DynamoDB

Open Amazon DynamoDB in the AWS Console.
Open the table named contact-form-data.
Click Explore Table Items.

You will see the submitted contact form data stored in the database.

